<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,503,743]" pageId="3" pageNumber="38">
Species of this genus are highly distinctive, because of the elongate, slender, eighth antennal segment that is about nine times as long as wide (
<figureCitation box="[461,545,540,564]" captionStart="FIGURES 8 – 14" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1910,1933]" captionTargetBox="[151,1431,265,1879]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,265,1889]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 8 – 14. Oxythrips and Projectothrips. O. australopalmae male 8 – 9: (8) terga VIII – IX; (9) sterna VI-VIII. P. beverlyae 10 – 14: (10) head &amp; thorax; (11) female; (12) male sterna V – VIII; (13) female terga VI – X; (14) antenna." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/276841/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="38">
Fig. 
<number box="[514,545,540,564]" pageId="3" pageNumber="38" value="14.0">14</number>
</figureCitation>
). Together with its generic synonym 
<emphasis box="[961,1109,540,564]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="38">Docidothrips</emphasis>
Priesner, the genus currently includes eight species. Each of these is known only from the Oriental and Pacific Regions, and they all live in the flowering spikes of 
<taxonomicName box="[375,487,612,636]" class="Liliopsida" family="Pandanaceae" genus="Pandanus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Pandanales" pageId="3" pageNumber="38" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[375,487,612,636]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="38">Pandanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species (screw pines). Collecting thrips from these flowers can be particularly difficult, and thus several of the species are known from few specimens with little information on intraspecific variation. The new species described below has been taken on two different species of 
<taxonomicName box="[1147,1259,684,708]" class="Liliopsida" family="Pandanaceae" genus="Pandanus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Pandanales" pageId="3" pageNumber="38" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1147,1259,684,708]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="38">Pandanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
at two widely separated localities.
</paragraph>
